2500|$|There {{is little}} extant {{evidence}} of any seals actually used by early U.S. presidents. [...] One possibility is a letter from 1835, sent from Paris to President Jackson and then forwarded to the Department of State. [...] The envelope has a small circular red <b>wax</b> <b>seal,</b> with the upper portion appearing to have a circle of cloud puffs similar to the Great Seal, with rays of a glory. [...] However, {{the rest of the}} design has been obliterated, so nothing further can be determined, and no other uses of this seal have been found.|$|E
