50|$|Among the {{earliest}} glass jars used for home canning were wax sealers, named {{in reference to}} the <b>sealing</b> <b>wax</b> that was poured into a channel around the lip to secure a tin lid. This process, which was complicated and error-prone, became popular in the late 1830s or early 1840s and was commonly used for sealing fruit jars from the early 1850s until about 1890. The <b>wax</b> <b>sealing</b> process was largely the only one available until other sealing methods were developed, and widely used into the early 1900s.|$|R
